│ Understanding the Issue: The transformation incorrectly folds `select (fcmp │
│ ole X, 0.0), (0.0 - X), X` to `fabs(X)` without considering NaN handling.   │
│ When X is a signaling NaN (SNaN), the original select yields the SNaN       │
│ (since fcmp ole returns false for NaN, so select picks X, which is SNaN).   │
│ The fabs intrinsic clears the sign bit of NaN, turning SNaN into a quiet    │
│ NaN (QNaN) with sign bit cleared. This changes the NaN payload (sign bit)   │
│ and may affect exception behavior. The transformation is only valid when we │
│ know NaNs cannot occur (nnan) or when the sign bit of NaN is irrelevant     │
│ (which is not guaranteed). The fsub pattern also flips the sign bit of NaN  │
│ when selected (if fcmp unordered true). However, the pattern uses           │
│ `m_PosZeroFP()` which ensures the zero is positive, but still the sign bit  │
│ of NaN matters.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows the              │
│ transformation occurs in `foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs`. The select has no      │
│ fast-math flags (no nnan, nsz). The fcmp is `ole` (ordered less or equal).  │
│ For NaN, ordered comparisons return false, so select picks X (the SNaN).    │
│ The fabs would produce a different NaN (sign bit cleared). This is a        │
│ mismatch.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The function                           │
│ `foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs` at lines 2796-2804 handles the pattern           │
│ `match(TrueVal, m_FSub(m_PosZeroFP(), m_Specific(X)))`. It checks           │
│ predicates OLE or ULE (for Swap false) and OGT or UGT (for Swap true).      │
│ However, it does not require any fast-math flags (nnan, nsz). The comment   │
│ at line 2776-2777 says \"We need fast-math-flags (nsz) or fsub with +0.0    │
│ (not fneg) for this to work.\" But the code does not enforce nnan. For      │
│ unordered predicates (ULE, UGT), NaN compares true, leading to selecting    │
│ TrueVal (0.0 - X) which flips the sign bit of NaN (since fsub with zero may │
│ propagate NaN sign? Actually 0.0 - SNaN yields QNaN with sign bit flipped?  │
│ The result is a quiet NaN with sign bit opposite of input? The spec says    │
│ subtraction of zero does not change NaN payload except sign bit may be      │
│ flipped? The fabs clears sign bit. So unordered predicates also need        │
│ nnan.\n\nThus the transformation must require `nnan` (and possibly `nsz`    │
│ for signed zero). The existing check for nsz/nnan is only for the fneg      │
│ pattern (line 2840). The fsub pattern should also require nnan (and maybe   │
│ nsz).\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): Modify lines 2796-2804 to add a check   │
│ for `SI.hasNoNaNs()` (and possibly `SI.hasNoSignedZeros()`). Since the      │
│ pattern uses positive zero, signed zero may be okay, but rounding modes     │
│ could affect zero sign. Safer to require nsz as well. However, the comment  │
│ says \"We need fast-math-flags (nsz) or fsub with +0.0 (not fneg) for this  │
│ to work.\" That suggests nsz is not required for fsub with positive zero    │
│ because positive zero ensures zero sign is positive. But rounding mode      │
│ could still produce -0.0? The subtraction 0.0 - X with rounding toward      │
│ negative could produce -0.0 when X is +0.0. That's a corner case. We'll     │
│ require nsz as well to be safe.\n\nWe'll add a condition before the         │
│ transformation: `if (!SI.hasNoNaNs() || !SI.hasNoSignedZeros())             │
│ continue;`\n\n5. Conclusion: The fix ensures the transformation only        │
│ applies when fast-math flags nnan and nsz are present, preserving           │
│ correctness for NaN and signed zero cases."}                                │
