│ SNaN). The fabs intrinsic clears the sign bit of NaN, turning SNaN into a   │
│ quiet NaN (QNaN) with sign bit cleared. This changes the NaN payload (sign  │
│ bit) and may affect exception behavior. The transformation is only valid    │
│ when we know NaNs cannot occur (nnan) or when the sign bit of NaN is        │
│ irrelevant (which is not guaranteed). The fsub pattern also flips the sign  │
│ bit of NaN when selected (if fcmp unordered true). However, the pattern     │
│ uses `m_PosZeroFP()` which ensures the zero is positive, but still the sign │
│ bit of NaN matters.                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows the transformation occurs in        │
│ `foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs`. The select has no fast-math flags (no nnan,     │
│ nsz). The fcmp is `ole` (ordered less or equal). For NaN, ordered           │
│ comparisons return false, so select picks X (the SNaN). The fabs would      │
│ produce a different NaN (sign bit cleared). This is a mismatch.             │
│                                                                             │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis: The function `foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs` at lines    │
│ 2796-2804 handles the pattern `match(TrueVal, m_FSub(m_PosZeroFP(),         │
│ m_Specific(X)))`. It checks predicates OLE or ULE (for Swap false) and OGT  │
│ or UGT (for Swap true). However, it does not require any fast-math flags    │
│ (nnan, nsz). The comment at line 2776-2777 says "We need fast-math-flags    │
│ (nsz) or fsub with +0.0 (not fneg) for this to work." But the code does not │
│ enforce nnan. For unordered predicates (ULE, UGT), NaN compares true,       │
│ leading to selecting TrueVal (0.0 - X) which flips the sign bit of NaN      │
│ (since fsub with zero may propagate NaN sign? Actually 0.0 - SNaN yields    │
│ QNaN with sign bit flipped? The result is a quiet NaN with sign bit         │
│ opposite of input? The spec says subtraction of zero does not change NaN    │
│ payload except sign bit may be flipped? The fabs clears sign bit. So        │
│ unordered predicates also need nnan.                                        │
│                                                                             │
│ Thus the transformation must require `nnan` (and possibly `nsz` for signed  │
│ zero). The existing check for nsz/nnan is only for the fneg pattern (line   │
│ 2840). The fsub pattern should also require nnan (and maybe nsz).           │
│                                                                             │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s): Modify lines 2796-2804 to add a check for        │
│ `SI.hasNoNaNs()` (and possibly `SI.hasNoSignedZeros()`). Since the pattern  │
│ uses positive zero, signed zero may be okay, but rounding modes could       │
